post_text:
Thank you, Naches Community! You far exceeded our expectations for our first day of the free meal program.

We are aware of the issues and glitches experienced today and are working to ensure that they are addressed quickly. Please bear with us as we work on the timing of the bus stops and improve our meal service procedures. We appreciate your patience and flexibility as we work through the challenges identified today.

You can also help us improve our bus stop timing by being at your stop approximately 5 minutes before your scheduled bus stop time. Additionally, we will attempt to communicate with you if we find that we are falling significantly behind schedule. We will adjust bus route times next week as we determine what adjustments are needed. We will announce the updated route times once they are posted.

Please remember to submit a Meal Delivery Consent Form if you haven’t already, so that we can continue to deliver a meal to your student. The form can be found on our website.

Thank you, again. We can’t do what we do without you.

Connectivity update #3

We have finished our second round of contacting people who signified they had no Internet at their home. If you are still unable to get the Internet, but do get cell service (Verizon) in your area, please contact the high school and talk to Tracie or Shelly. If you know of a family that has no Internet, please mention to them they can call the high school and request a hot spot.

We also have some extras, so if you have multiple kids in your household and would benefit from another hot spot, please reach out as well. We want to make sure we are using these resources. High school phone #- (509) 653-1732.
Thank you

FREE MEAL DELIVERY FOR ALL CHILDREN AGES 1-18 (regardless of eligibility or enrollment status; must be in the NVSD area)

WHEN: Beginning Wednesday, September 9, on school days

WHO: All children ages 1 to 18 in the Naches Valley School District area, regardless of eligibility or enrollment status

HOW: Each child will receive two meals, served at the same time: lunch for that day and breakfast for the following morning. All meals include entree, fruit and/or veggies, milk.

WHERE: At regularly scheduled bus stops. See bus routes on our website.

ONE-TIME CONSENT FORM REQUIRED: Online at: https://forms.gle/d9oP1GxNui1oZHov9 or available from bus driver.

2020/21 Food Service Information

We will begin delivering meals by bus or district vehicle on Wednesday, August 26, to students who are enrolled in our district and who have pre-ordered a meal. Breakfast and lunch will be delivered at the same time if both are ordered.

Orders must be submitted by 5:00am of the day of service in order to receive a meal that day. We will be using a Google Form for meal orders. Please submit one form per student. The order form can be found here: https://forms.gle/8YmHikLdEcLQRPqG9. (We are required to verify student enrollment status before serving a meal.)

Additional information, including meal delivery bus stops, free/reduced-price lunch application information, and lunch account payment information can be found on our website at: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1JGPkvdtFng-m6YWGfW7KR7q24HW1vzNZ/view

We will be delivering meals by bus or district vehicle to students enrolled in our district who have pre-ordered a meal while we are in Continuous Learning 2.0 education model.

Unfortunately, USDA guidelines require that we return to our normal meal charging process for meals served in 2020/21.

As a result, a student's eligibility of free, reduced, or paid status will apply to delivered meals.

Additional details, ordering instructions, and contact information will be sent through Skyward before the first day of school. Bus routes will be posted to our website soon.

Evening Chromebook handout:
On Monday the 24 of August, the Elementary school, Middle school and High school will have an evening handout of Chromebooks, from 5 to 7 pm.. At the es and ms, please just pull up and there will be people outside to hand out a Chromebook or swap one out if needed. At the high school, please pull up and go into the office.. we will be limiting people coming in to 2 maximum. All incoming Freshman should exchange their MS Chromebook for a high school one.

On Tuesday the 25th, the Middle school will have another evening of handing out Chromebooks from 5 to 7 pm. The elementary and high school just ask that you call and they can arrange a time for you to come in if you missed the evening of the 24th.

Please remember to charge the Chromebook, confirm log in.. make sure its up and working. If not please reach out to the building Secretary. We really want to make the start of the school year as smooth as possible. Thank you

post_text:
Attention Kindergarten Parents:

As you know, due to COVID-19, we may be asked to return to school virtually to start the 2020-21 school year. If that is the case, are you wondering what Kindergarten is going to look like in a virtual format?

We are so excited to begin our educational journey together and we want to share the fun and exciting things that we are planning for you.

Please join, along with your student, our Zoom meeting on Thursday, Aug. 13th at 7:00 PM. We will be hosting a community forum for Kindergarten parents and students to come meet us on zoom.

Agenda

Brief Explanation of our Virtual Model
Kindergarten Schedule
Screening Information
Registration Information
Meet the Kindergarten Teachers
Teachers’ examples of their virtual classrooms
Fun student activity
Q & A

We are looking forward to hearing you Thursday 8/13/2020 at 7:00 PM.

The following link to be taken to the community forum meeting: https://zoom.us/j/93630635056

Sincerely,
Eric Valentine
Principal
Naches Valley Elementary School

post_text:
Dear Community,

I know there are still many questions around our reopening plan and what it looks like for students come the fall. Though we will render an official decision on Monday, based on the recommendations from both the Department of Health and the Yakima Health District today, it is very likely that Naches Valley will be in a fully online format to begin the school year.

We will release our full detailed plan Tuesday morning at 9:00 via email, our webpage, Facebook, and ePride. We will also be holding virtual community meetings for each school to lay out details and answer questions. Those dates will be released on Tuesday as well.

Respectfully,
Robert Bowman - Superintendent

post_text:
A heartfelt thank you goes out to our four retirees this year. Due to COVID, we weren't able to send them off in style...(don't worry that WILL happen when we return to normal).

That said, the accumulated time and expertise these four professionals exhibited is amazing. Combined, they have over 97 years of experience!

When you think about how many lives they've touched and helped over that span of that time, it's literally incalculable how many students and adults they've helped. You are treasures that will be missed greatly!

To say thank you seems like it's not enough, but please know that you are so appreciated for all you've done in service of kids at Naches Valley.

It truly is a great day to be a RETIRED Ranger! :)

post_text:
It's Teacher Appreciation Week, and even though we aren't in "traditional" school, teachers are working hard to engage students and help them learn through a really tough time.

Being a teacher means making connections with students and families, helping a child through a tough time, pushing kids to give their best effort and self, and ultimately be there when they need us.

So a huge thank you goes out to our teachers and for all they do in service of our students and our futures.

KINDERGARTEN REGISTRATION OPEN

If your child will be five years of age on or before August 31, 2020, they are eligible to attend kindergarten in the 2020-2021 school year.

This year, enrollment will take place on-line at www.nvsd.org (click on the Kindergarten Registration Packet link) or www.rangercubs.nvsd.org.

Naches Valley High School will be participating in the "Be the Light" national movement in recognition for the Class of 2020 this coming Friday, April 17th.

At 8:20 pm (20:20 Military Time), the High School Football Stadium lights will be on for 20 minutes in recognition of not only the 2020 Senior Athletes but the 2020 Senior Class who have not only lost their athletic seasons but Senior Events as well.

This event will be designed to be a drive-thru event as we want to ensure the public that we are keeping with recommended social distancing, the stadium, fields and parking lots will be off-limits.

For the 20 minutes that the lights are on please feel free to drive through, snap some pictures to post on Social Media and wave to those who may be there. Hope to see you Friday! #BeTheLightWA

The Naches Valley School District continues to monitor the COVID situation closely.

This morning, local area superintendents and the Yakima Health Dept. met to debrief the situation. As of now, the recommendation of the Health Dept. is that schools should remain open. This, of course, is subject to change, and we are meeting daily to assess.

As noted before, we've canceled all non-essential meetings. In regards to spring sports, we are continuing to practice, however, any games or events/matches will be moved to after Spring Break, and again, these are subject to change.

Update March 11, 2020

As you are probably aware, Pierce, Snohomish and King counties are all waiting for the Governor to make a decision by tomorrow whether he will order a school closures for that region that may last until April 24th.

The goal of closing school is to slow the spread of the outbreak by reducing social interactions. The modeling shows infection rates double every 5-8 days.

As of now, Naches Valley School District is running as normal. We will, of course, keep you posted should anything change.

Classified schools employees are involved in nearly every aspect of eduction, whether that’s maintaining buildings and grounds, preparing and serving meals, keeping school facilities clean and orderly, assisting in the classrooms, keeping offices running smoothly, transporting kids safely, creating a healthy environment, and many other services...without their help and expertise, there’s no way we could function effectively.

These dedicated folks deserve recognition and thanks for the outstanding work they’re doing in service of kids. I know that we don’t say it enough, but THANK YOU to all of our classified staff for all they do.

It’s classified employee week in Naches Valley. If you see one of these dedicated individuals this week, give ‘em a high five, thank them for their service.

I know that I am grateful for their dedication to all of our students!
-Robert Bowman, Superintendent

post_text:
As we are aware, this is Ms. Schnebly's last year as principal at our elementary, so the last couple of evenings have been spent interviewing strong candidates for the upcoming job, which starts up next school year.

2 committees convened (both an administrative committee and an elementary committee) made up of elementary staff, parents, administrators and Board members. Each committee had a chance to interview each top candidate.

The unanimous choice for the next principal was Eric Valentine, our current vice-principal at the elementary. Congratulations to him, and a shout out to all the committee members for their time and effort these last couple of evenings.

It's a great day to be a Ranger!

post_text:
Poetry Out Loud is a national arts education program that encourages the study of great poetry through dynamic recitation competition in high schools across the country. This program helps students master public speaking skills, build self-confidence, and learn about literary history and contemporary life. Wednesday night 21 Naches students competed at the high school, reading 2 poems each for a total of 42 poems performed, which were scored by a panel of judges.

Congratulations to all who participated and a special shout out goes to sophomore Emily Stout, winning the competition as well as runner up senior Kyle Buckles. Both of them will compete at the regional competition on Sunday, January 26th at YVC Kendall hall at 2:00. The top two finishers will advance to state in Tacoma in March.
text:
Poetry Out Loud is a national arts education program that encourages the study of great poetry through dynamic recitation competition in high schools across the country. This program helps students master public speaking skills, build self-confidence, and learn about literary history and contemporary life. Wednesday night 21 Naches students competed at the high school, reading 2 poems each for a total of 42 poems performed, which were scored by a panel of judges.

Congratulations to all who participated and a special shout out goes to sophomore Emily Stout, winning the competition as well as runner up senior Kyle Buckles. Both of them will compete at the regional competition on Sunday, January 26th at YVC Kendall hall at 2:00. The top two finishers will advance to state in Tacoma in March.

With possible inclement weather coming in late tonight/early tomorrow morning, we just wanted to remind everyone that when bad weather hits Naches Valley, we know that our families and staff are anxiously awaiting to hear what our district and schools have planned. If we make a change from our normal operations, we will post information on these platforms (in this order) by 6 a.m., if not sooner.

1. Local TV and media
2. Our Webpage (www.nvsd.org) and our recorded message at: 509-653-2220
3. School Messenger (mass email / automated phone call)
4. Facebook.

The District transportation staff checks road conditions and monitors the weather overnight. Transportation staff
drive the roads beginning 3:30 a.m. to assess conditions.

Ultimately, the superintendent makes all decisions to change school operating schedules based on the weather, road and driving conditions.

With temperatures getting very COLD the next few days, it's a reminder we are quickly approaching the time of year that often brings weather conditions that can potentially impact school schedules.

You can find information about weather-related decisions via the following:

Robocall, text message and email - We send out messaging through a variety of communication channels in order to adequately reach the community.

FlashAlert - You can subscribe to email and text updates through FlashAlert. This is the same notification system that television and radio stations use to get updates about school delays and closures. If you sign up for these alerts, it will be in addition to the notifications the school district sends. You can sign up at http://www.flashalert.net/signup/.

District website - A message will be posted to the front page of our district website.

Social media - Messages will be posted to the district Facebook page.

post_text:
On Saturday October 26th the Ranger marching band traveled to Washington State University to compete against 16 other bands from all over Washington, Idaho, Oregan, and Montana. The 16 band were split between 4 different divisions based on band size for preliminary competition. NVHS competed in the A Class and received Best Color Guard performance, Best Music Performance, and 1st overall in their division. In finals all bands competed against each other and Naches received 11th overall. It has been a wonderful marching band season with a lot of improvement.

Cavalcade of Bands - Pasco Washington: 2nd Place A Division, Best Auxiliary, Best Percussion, and Best Visual.

Harvest Marching Band Festival - Yakima Washington: 1st Place in A Division, Best Marching and Best Auxiliary, 11th overall in Finals competition.

Washington State University Marching Band Championships - Pullman Washington: 1st Place in A Division, Best Music and Best Auxiliary, 11th overall in Finals competition.

Congratulations to the high school. The Yakima Herald Republic published an article today highlighting local districts, including Naches which has the lowest drop out rate in the county at 2.7%, well under the state rate of 11.2%.

Naches has a graduation rate of 92%, whereas county-wide, the average is 73%.

It's a great day to be a Ranger!

If you haven't been down by the elementary school lately, you might be surprised to see so many vehicles, tents, and over 650 firefighters. I had the chance to get a tour of the operation as well as a debrief on the progress of the fire. I was impressed by the dedication and thoroughness of the people and operation.

I'm very glad the District is able to help whenever and however we can. Here's hoping for a speedy and safe containment. Thank you firefighters!

post_text:
Superintendent Search

This week on Tuesday and Thursday the Board interviewed the following candidates for the superintendent position. Brett Baum, Middle School Principal, Okanogan SD, Jennifer Kindle, Executive Director of Student Learning, Selah SD, James Heinle, Middle School Principal, Grandview SD, Robert Bowman, Middle School Principal, Sunnyside SD, Kelly Thorson, Tieton Intermediate School, Highland SD, and John Hannah, Superintendent, Morton SD, The interviews were observed by the district staff, parents and community members and their feedback was given to the Board. Three finalist will be chosen from this field for all day interviews on Monday, March 4th, Tuesday, March 5th and Thursday, March 7th. During these interviews there will be an opportunity to meet each candidate, ask questions and again provide written feedback to the School Board.

post_text:
No students were on the bus... but it did go off the road. At 5:30 am the road was fine (we do check every morning!) but between then and when the buses rolled out, a band of freezing rain crossed the Nile road right by the upper Nile bridge. We were able to retrieve the bus (with the help of two tow trucks) and were able to bring the students home in the afternoon. The first folks on the scene reported the road was so slippery you could not stand up on it. THANKS to our intrepid bus drivers who deal with all types of road conditions every single day.

So, even though we do check the roads, if you see late developing unsafe conditions, please give us a call at 509-653-1817 (transportation) or 509-653-1800 (Superintendent). Please leave us a message if we cannot answer immediately.

post_text:
Frequently Asked Questions
About Negotiations, Financial Issues and staffing

Do teachers deserve more pay? Absolutely. Naches Valley School District prides itself on the quality of its teachers. Nothing makes a bigger difference for students than providing them with world-class teachers. While our salaries are not the highest in the region, we have worked hard over the years to 'keep pace'. With the new inequitable funding formula from the state and each district negotiating their own salary schedules, we are struggling to 'keep pace' with districts in the state. This will affect our teachers now and may in the future, affect our families and students.
We understand this is a very stressful time for our staff, community and board members. There have been some good questions asked and limited good information available. With this in mind, we want to share answers and provide information about teacher salary negotiations and our financial position.

Here are answers to questions posed to the board or emailed to us: https://goo.gl/jXYppN

Any senior that plans to attend any type of post-high school education should plan to attend with their parent/guardian. The FAFSA (Free Application for Federal Student Aid) will be open on October 1st. Washington state is still first come, first serve for financial aid assistance. Students/families should complete the FAFSA as soon as they possibly can from the opening date. Students must complete the FAFSA to be considered for ANY kind of financial aid from higher education institutions.

Our dismissal will be on-time following usual procedures.

post_text:
Improve Success by Spurring One Simple Habit

Do you want to improve success at school, in your job and in your life? What about improving success for your children at school? It turns out that there's a very simple nightly ritual that some of the world's most successful people employ. And best of all, it's completely free.

According to an article from Ladders, media magnate Oprah Winfrey, Facebook COO Sheryl Sandberg, and others all count their blessings before fading off to sleep every night.

The most successful people, like Winfrey and Sandberg, keep a gratitude journal. Rather than thinking about what went wrong in a day, they think about what went right and what they're thankful for each night before going to bed. A 2011 study from Applied Psychology: Health and Well-Being showed that students who took 15 minutes at night to write a gratitude journal slept better and longer. Improved sleep has been proven many times over to improve performance, especially academic performance.

Come one come all to the Wonderful World of School Bus Driving. Where else can you go and get paid to drive a school bus full of energy. Perfect for the parent/guardian that needs something to do during the day but wants to be home when their students get out of school and during the holiday/summer vacations. Imagine no more worrying about child care. The morning fun starts about 6:00 and runs to 8:00 AM. Afternoon shifts are from 2:20 until 4:15 PM. Trips are also available to drive for sports or extracurricular activities during the week and on Saturdays. Wages begin at $18.60 per hour. Free training available. IF you do not want to drive every day, sign up as a substitute and to help with sports and activity bus runs!

Please contact the transportation department for details.
We hope to hear from you soon.

Carrie Rebuck - Driver Trainer 509-653-1817
LaDonna Berkey - Transportation Director 509-653-1816

post_text: The Naches Cheer squad attended a leadership camp through National Cheerleaders Association at Central Washington University this summer. Each summer at UCA, UDA, NCA, NDA, and USA camps, thousands of cheerleaders and dancers try out for the All-American title by performing a spirited routine, but only 10 percent are chosen. Four of our Naches cheerleaders were chosen to try out for this high honor; Christina Woodall, Lizzie Rockwell, Lydia Cuyle, and Morgan Young. After auditions, two of the girls were selected as All-American Cheerleaders, Morgan Young and Lydia Cuyle. Being an All-American is one of the highest awards an individual can achieve in cheerleading. As part of this special honor Morgan and Lydia were invited to perform in the New Years Day parade in London this year. Congratulations to the all of the Naches Cheerleaders for their great accomplishments!

post_text:
Outdoor Air Quality is "unhealthy"!
With the smoke in the air, we are keeping students inside in all the buildings instead of outside recess and breaks. When the smoke clears out some and the Air Quality returns to moderate or better, we will resume outdoor recess and athletic practices and games. The question has come up about cancelling school, but we believe that students are as safe and healthy here as they are in most homes. Our filter systems do reduce the amount of indoor 'particulates' or tiny particles of smoke in the air.

post_text:
We start our Art program early! During the month of April, the special education preschool students studied the masters. They followed examples of different artists and their genre's giving them the opportunity to explore different techniques and mediums. The process of creating artwork fostered brain development in such areas as cognitive, social-emotional, and multi-sensory skills. Not only did they have fun creating, they were learning! (Thanks to Teacher Tara Jacobs!)

Photo 1: Monet's "Water Lily Pond"
Photo 2: Mondrian's "Composition II in Red, Blue, and Yellow"
Photo 3: Pollock's splatter painting technique. This was a favorite for all of us! Who doesn't like being super messy.
Photo 4: Picasso's cubism deconstruction and reconstruction.

Naches Valley Middle School 8th Graders attended the JA Finance Park in Yakima on March 24. Junior Achievement (JA) is a philanthropic organzation that partners with area businesses to help schools provide student understanding of economics and personal finance.

8th Graders studied a 13 part course in personal finance to prepare for activities at the Junior Achievement World located on University Parkway in Terrace Heights. At the facitily, students prepared personal budgets and learned the realities of paying bills, budgeting for life, and saving money.

"This is a great opportunity for our students in a lot of different ways," remarked 8th grade Math Teacher Ilene Rust. "It's a fantastic way to get kids into a simulation where they have to apply classroom and financial learning."

Thanks to JA World and its sponsors for this opportunity!

post_text: Our exemplary performance on signing up middle school students for the College Bound Scholarship program was recently recognized by the state. The Naches Valley School District received the Gold Star Award for being one of the top-performing districts in the state for College Bound Scholarship sign-ups. The College Bound Scholarship program encourages Washington students to pursue educational opportunities beyond high school. Qualifying students must sign up by the end of their 8th grade year at the middle school and our efforts achieved a sign-up rate greater than the state average. For further information or qualification specifics about this program please call the middle school counselor, Jayann Cruzen at 653-1599.

All of us here at Naches Valley School District want to say "THANK YOU" to all of our support staff who keep us organized (secretaries), keep us fed (food service), keep things healthy and clean (custodians), keep things fixed (maintenance), get us to and from school safely (bus drivers and mechanics), help out in our classrooms (para-educators), comfort the afflicted (nurse assistant), help us communicate (speech and language pathologist assistants), keep us reading (library para) and accompany our efforts with music (accompanist)!

We do appreciate your hard work and your caring and your friendship this day, this week and EVERY DAY of the school year.

THANKS

Duane Lyons
Superintendent of Schools
Naches Valley School District
text:
All of us here at Naches Valley School District want to say "THANK YOU" to all of our support staff who keep us organized (secretaries), keep us fed (food service), keep things healthy and clean (custodians), keep things fixed (maintenance), get us to and from school safely (bus drivers and mechanics), help out in our classrooms (para-educators), comfort the afflicted (nurse assistant), help us communicate (speech and language pathologist assistants), keep us reading (library para) and accompany our efforts with music (accompanist)!

We do appreciate your hard work and your caring and your friendship this day, this week and EVERY DAY of the school year.

THANKS

Duane Lyons
Superintendent of Schools
Naches Valley School District

post_text:
Ever Hear of the Magdeburg Water Bridge? Neither Had We!

Thirty-three 5th graders competed, during the last 5 weeks, in a geography-based contest, against schools from all over the world. Every team sent in clues that described a famous landmark. We spent 3 weeks researching clues and carefully choosing a yes/no question to email to each team. By the end of school on Friday, we still had not decided on one of our final landmark guesses. Passionate and dedicated students voluntarily kept their parents waiting while they deduced their last landmark guess, by 3:30 PM!
We received our results this morning and were thrilled to discover that our little team of 5th graders placed first out of 23 teams! See results in the chart below. To see more information on the contest, go to http://www.kidlink.org/drupal/project/landmark

Congratulations to the hard working, dedicated, inquisitive kids of Landmarks 2017... especially the NVMS Team (pictured)!

post_text: On Monday, March 27th, NVMS 7th graders will be hearing a first person account of one of the Lost Boys of Sudan. Students have read the novel, "A Long Walk to Water", by Linda Sue Park, and studied the Southern Sudanese War. Abraham Abei was part of the group Salva Dut led out of Ethiopia to Kenya. He has now settled in Seattle. We are honored to have him come share his story with our students.

The Academic Opportunities Committee meeting has been rescheduled for next Tuesday January 31 at 6 pm in The Den at the Elementary School to map out the next stage of information-gathering to garner ideas and inspiration for potential K-12 academic enrichment opportunities at Naches.

This spring, the committee will be interviewing school districts of similar size, economic make-up or student body, to learn what other schools are doing in terms of academic offerings, how they fund those opportunities, and other curriculum enrichment activities they employ. This effort depends on the involvement of interested parents, teachers and staff to develop interview questions and strategic approach, and to conduct the interviews. Please let us know if you can come!

Sincerely,
Katrina Strathmann, Marcie Carrell and Patti Hyatt (of the AE Committee)

Flu activity is on the rise in Washington! There are steps you can take right now to reduce your risk of exposure and minimize the chance of spreading disease. Flu vaccination is the best method of prevention, followed by covering your cough/proper hand washing and staying home from school or work when you are sick. The flu shot does take up to 2 weeks to provide full protection, but is available right now at pharmacies and clinic locations throughout the state.

After getting vaccinated, protect yourself from flu by doing the following:

Little girls with boxing gloves fighting flu

The WA Department of Health offers resources and information on their dedicated flu webpage. Here is the link.

http://www.doh.wa.gov/YouandYourFamily/IllnessandDisease/Flu
